ement" style="height: 268.8px;">222</div><div class="cm-gutterElement" style="height: 1411.2px;">223</div></div><div class="cm-gutter cm-foldGutter"><div class="cm-gutterElement" style="height: 0px; visibility: hidden; pointer-events: none;"><span title="Unfold line">▸</span></div><div class="cm-gutterElement" style="height: 22.4px; margin-top: 7217.6px;"><span title="Fold line">▾</span></div><div class="cm-gutterElement" style="height: 44.8px; margin-top: 717.2px;"><span title="Fold line">▾</span></div></div><div class="cm-gutter cm-gutter-lint"></div></div><div style="tab-size: 4; --half-leading: 4.4px; padding-bottom: 736.6px;" spellcheck="false" autocorrect="off" autocapitalize="none" writingsuggestions="false" translate="no" contenteditable="true" class="cm-content cm-lineWrapping" role="textbox" aria-multiline="true" aria-label="Source Editor editing" data-language="latex" aria-autocomplete="list"><div class="cm-gap" style="height: 5645px;"></div><div class="cm-line"><span class="cm-matchingBracket">(</span>a loop on a vertex $v$ would yield two angles corresponding to the same pair $(v,f)$. From this is easy to give counterexamples even in the loop-free case.<span class="cm-matchingBracket">)</span></div><div class="cm-gap" style="height: 1254.8px;"></div><div class="cm-line">The pictorial rule for constructing <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-literal">\dmg</span> <span class="tok-string">G</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> from <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-string">G</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> is recalled in Figure <span class="tok-keyword">\ref</span><span class="tok-punctuation">{</span><span class="tok-attributeValue">fig-directed-medial-graph-construction</span><span class="tok-punctuation">}</span>. </div><div class="cm-line"><img class="cm-widgetBuffer" aria-hidden="true"><span class="ol-cm-filler" contenteditable="false"></span><br></div><div class="cm-line"><span class="tok-typeName">\begin</span><span class="tok-punctuation">{</span><span class="tok-attributeValue">figure</span><span class="tok-punctuation">}</span><span class="tok-punctuation">[</span>htp<span class="tok-punctuation">]</span></div><div class="cm-indent-markers cm-line" style="text-indent: -4ch; padding-left: calc(4ch + 6px); --indent-markers: repeating-linear-gradient(to right, var(--indent-marker-bg-color) 0 1px, transparent 1.2px 4ch) 4.5ch/calc(0ch - 1px) no-repeat;">    <span class="tok-typeName">\centering</span>   <span class="tok-typeName">\includegraphics</span><span class="tok-punctuation">[</span>width=0.8700<span class="tok-typeName">\textwidth</span><span class="tok-punctuation">]</span><span class="tok-punctuation">{</span><span class="tok-attributeValue">Immagini/directed-medial-graph-construction.jpeg</span><span class="tok-punctuation">}</span></div><div class="cm-indent-markers cm-line" style="text-indent: -4ch; padding-left: calc(4ch + 6px); --indent-markers: repeating-linear-gradient(to right, var(--indent-marker-bg-color) 0 1px, transparent 1.2px 4ch) 4.5ch/calc(0ch - 1px) no-repeat;">    <span class="tok-typeName">\caption</span><span class="tok-punctuation">{</span>Construction rule of the directed medial graph.<span class="tok-punctuation">}</span></div><div class="cm-indent-markers cm-line" style="text-indent: -4ch; padding-left: calc(4ch + 6px); --indent-markers: repeating-linear-gradient(to right, var(--indent-marker-bg-color) 0 1px, transparent 1.2px 4ch) 4.5ch/calc(0ch - 1px) no-repeat;">    <span class="tok-keyword">\label</span><span class="tok-punctuation">{</span><span class="tok-attributeValue">fig-directed-medial-graph-construction</span><span class="tok-punctuation">}</span></div><div class="cm-line" style="text-indent: -1ch; padding-left: calc(1ch + 6px);"> <span class="tok-typeName">\end</span><span class="tok-punctuation">{</span><span class="tok-attributeValue">figure</span><span class="tok-punctuation">}</span></div><div class="cm-line"><img class="cm-widgetBuffer" aria-hidden="true"><span class="ol-cm-filler" contenteditable="false"></span><br></div><div class="cm-line">Notice that for any edge <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-string">e</span><span class="tok-literal">\in</span> <span class="tok-string">E_G</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> there are exactly two angles in <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-string">A_G</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> for which <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-string">e</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> is a source and exactly two angles for which <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-string">e</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> is a target. Equivalently, each vertex <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-literal">\dmg</span><span class="tok-string">(e)</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> in <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-literal">\dmg</span> <span class="tok-string">G</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> is the source of two arrows and the target of other two arrows. In particular, each vertex in </div><div class="cm-line" style="text-indent: -1ch; padding-left: calc(1ch + 6px);"> <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-literal">\dmg</span> <span class="tok-string">G</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> is quadrivalent.</div><div class="cm-line"><img class="cm-widgetBuffer" aria-hidden="true"><span class="ol-cm-filler" contenteditable="false"></span><br></div><div class="cm-line"><span class="tok-typeName">\begin</span><span class="tok-punctuation">{</span><span class="tok-attributeValue">remark</span><span class="tok-punctuation">}</span><span class="tok-keyword">\label</span><span class="tok-punctuation">{</span><span class="tok-attributeValue">rem.bounded</span><span class="tok-punctuation">}</span></div><div class="cm-line">We are not going to make explicit use of this fact, but it is worth noticing that if <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-string">G</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> is a connected planar graph, then the directed graph <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-literal">\dmg</span> <span class="tok-string">G</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> is strongly connected, <span class="ol-cm-spelling-error">i.e</span>., every two vertices <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-literal">\dmg</span> <span class="tok-string">(e_1)</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> and <span class="tok-string">$</span><span class="tok-literal">\dmg</span> <span class="tok-string">(e_2)</span><span class="tok-string">$</span> are connected by an oriented path. </div><div class="cm-line"><span class="tok-comment">% Indeed, let $e_1$ and $e_2$ be two edges of $G$, and let $f_1$ and $f_2$ be two faces of $G$ having $e_1$ and $e_2$ in their boundaries, respectively. The dual graph $\hat{G}$ of $G$ is connected. We look at $\hat{G}$ as an unoriented graph and consider the path distance on it. To prove that $e_1$ and $e_2$ are the endpoints of an angular path in $G$ one reasons inductively on the path distance of $f_1$ and $f_2$ in $\hat{G}$. If $\mathrm{dist}(f_1,f_2)=0$, then $f_1=f_2$, so $e_1$ and $e_2$ are edges in the same face of $G$. In this case there is clearly an angular path from $e_1$ to $e_2$. If $\mathrm{dist}(f_1,f_2)=1$, then $f_1$ and $f_2$ share a common edge $e$. One has an angular path from $e_1$ to $e$ consisting of angles in $f_1$ and an angular path from $e$ to $e_2$ consisting of angles in $f_2$. Assuming the statement is true for $\mathrm{dist}(f_1,f_2)\leq n$ with $n\geq 1$, it is then immediate to prove it for $\mathrm{dist}(f_1,f_2)\leq n+1$: if $f_1=\tilde{f}_0,\tilde{f}_1,\dots, \tilde{f}_n, \tilde{f}_{n+1}=f_2$ is a sequence of faces of $G$ such that $\tilde{f}_i$ and $\tilde{f}_{i+1}$ have a common edge, let $e$ be a common edge between $\tilde{f}_{n}$ and $f_2$. By the induction assumption one has an angular path from $e_1$ to $e$ and an angular path from $e$ to $e_2$. </span></div><div class="cm-gap" style="height: 40253px;"></div></div><div class="cm-layer cm-layer-above cm-cursorLayer" aria-hidden="true" style="z-index: 150; animation-duration: 1200ms; animation-name: cm-blink;"><div class="cm-cursor cm-cursor-primary" style="left: 263.4px; top: 5783.4px; height: 22.4px;"></div></div><div class="cm-layer cm-selectionLayer" aria-hidden="true" style="z-index: -2;"></div><div class="cm-layer cm-layer-above ol-cm-cursorHighlightsLayer" aria-hidden="true" style="z-index: 148;"></div><div class="cm-layer ol-cm-activeLineLayer" aria-hidden="true" style="z-index: -4;"><div class="cm-activeLine" style="left: 88.7333px; top: 5783.4px; width: 225.767px; height: 22.4px;"></div></div><div class="review-mode-switcher-container"><div class="review-mode-switcher dropdown"><button class="review-mode-switcher-toggle-button editing" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Editing"><span class="material-symbols" aria-hidden="true" translate="no">edit</span><div class="review-mode-switcher-toggle-label">Editing</div><span class="material-symbols" aria-hidden="true" translate="no">keyboard_arrow_down</span></button></div></div><div class="review-panel-container review-panel-mini" data-testid="review-panel" style="--review-panel-top: 100.56666564941406px; --review-panel-height: 50672px;"><div id="review-panel-inner" class="review-panel-inner"><div role="tabpanel" id="review-panel-current-file" aria-labelledby="review-panel-tab-button-current-file"><div></div></div><div class="review-panel-footer" id="review-panel-tabs" role="tablist"><button role="tab" aria-selected="true" aria-controls="review-panel-current-file" id="review-panel-tab-button-current-file" class="review-panel-tab review-panel-tab-active"><span class="material-symbols" aria-hidden="true" translate="no">description</span>Current file</button><button role="tab" aria-selected="false" aria-controls="review-panel-overview" id="review-panel-tab-button-overview" 